						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Freedom-to-Innovate-Biotechnology-in-Africa-s-Development.-Report-of-the-High-Level-African-Panel-on-Modern-Biotechnology" title="Freedom to Innovate: Biotechnology in Africa's Development. Report of the High-Level African Panel on Modern Biotechnology" alt="link">Freedom to Innovate: Biotechnology in Africa's Development. Report of the High-Level African Panel on Modern Biotechnology</a></h2>

	
					<p> This report is about the role of biotechnology in the transformation of African economies. The implications of its recommendations, however, need to be seen beyond the confines of biological innovations. They address critical issues related to Africa's place in a globalizing economy. Undertaken at the request of heads of state and government this report demonstrates what is needed to build the required capacity to harness and apply biotechnologies to improve agricultural productivity, public health, industrial development, economic competitiveness, and environmental sustainability (including biodiversity conservation) in Africa. It also shows that the measures needed to address biotechnology will strengthen Africa's capacity to adapt other technologies to economic development. In fact, previous inabilities to build capacity in fields such as information technology hamper the continent's efforts in biotechnology. This report has placed these systemic considerations in the context of the role of innovation in economic transformation. It challenges Africa's heads of state and government to take seriously the importance of a coordinated approach in promoting technological innovation in development. (Source: Calestous Juma and Ismail Serageldin, African Union/NEPADST, 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Freedom-to-Innovate-Biotechnology-in-Africa-s-Development.-Report-of-the-High-Level-African-Panel-on-Modern-Biotechnology">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-Technology-and-Skills" title="Science, Technology and Skills" alt="link">Science, Technology and Skills</a></h2>

	
					<p> The invention of agriculture that occurred around 10,000 years ago heralded a shift from nomadic hunting and gathering to more managed forms of food, feed and fiber production. Since then, agricultural innovation and research has produced great results in feeding the earth's population. This report looks at the changing context of agricultural research and development (R&amp;D), including the economic realities of agricultural R&amp;D; changing incentives to innovate; collective action in R&amp;D, and financing of R&amp;D. The report also looks at the state of sciences for agriculture as well as technological distance, spillovers, and knowledge stocks. The final section of the paper deals with technological risk and how to regulate technology in the agricultural sector. (Source: P. Pardey et al., Working Paper 41371, World Bank, 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/Science-Technology-and-Skills">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
